    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/147c5a9cc1feec049c50da791ac7d144?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 47283,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 139985,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/139985/stephen-c",
                "reputation": 723464,
                "display_name": "Stephen C",
                "accept_rate": 69
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1377656119,
            "creation_date": 1377656119,
            "body": "<p>It is technically possible to do that, but it is not a good idea:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>Any fixed partitioning has a risk that the worker thread workloads will be unbalanced.  The time taken to finish the parallel part of the computation is the maximum of the times of each of the worker threads.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>The <code>ArrayList<\/code> could become a contention bottleneck, especially if the threads need to update it.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>A better approach is to use a queuing mechanism with the workers all taking work from the same queue.  And a simple way to implement this is to use an <code>ExecutorService<\/code> with a bounded worker pool.  (The fork-join framework is another possibility, though that is more suited to dynamic or recursive tasks where there are dependencies between the tasks.)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18478358,
            "question_id": 18478292
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/NMBDq.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1244574,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1206301,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1206301/alexei-kaigorodov",
                "reputation": 13605,
                "display_name": "Alexei Kaigorodov",
                "accept_rate": 10
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1377674040,
            "creation_date": 1377674040,
            "body": "<p>For you case, optimal is to use one thread reading urls from excel file and putting it in an ArrayBlockingQueue with limited capacity. Start several working threads which take urls one by one and scrape the referenced site. Standard thread pool would not help, as each piece of work needs blocking while accessing site, and thread pools do not like when their threads are blocked. The only parameter which needs tweaking is the number of working threads. Try 10, 100, 1000, 10000 to find out the fastest configuration. If for several thousands of threads, memory is exhausted but the optimum is not reached, then switch to some NIO library like Netty.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18481496,
            "question_id": 18478292
        }
    ],
